ROOT CAUSE: `src/be_strlib.c:497-560` — `str_format` has no handling for the `%%` escape (literal `%`). After `get_mode` advances past the `%`, `*p` is `'%'`, but before the `switch` the code unconditionally enforces `if (index > top) be_raise(...)`. So `s.format("%%")` (top=1, index=2) raises "bad argument #2 to 'format': no value" instead of emitting a literal `%`. Even if an argument were supplied, control would fall into the `default` branch and raise "invalid option '%%'". Compare with `be_pushvfstr` (line 170+) which correctly handles `%%` with `format = p + 2`.

LOCAL FIX: In `str_format`, handle `%%` before consuming an argument. Replace the block starting at line 514 with:

```c
buf[0] = '\0';
if (*p == '%') {                    /* literal %% */
    be_pushstring(vm, "%");
    concat2(vm);
    format = p + 1;
    continue;                       /* do not advance index */
}
if (index > top) {
    be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
        "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
}
switch (*p) { ... }
```

(Equivalently, add `case '%': be_pushstring(vm, "%"); break;` to the switch and skip the `++index` / `index>top` check when `*p=='%'`.)

GLOBAL FIX: Eliminate the duplicated, hand-rolled format parser. `str_format` and `be_pushvfstr` both walk a printf-style format string with subtly different rules (`be_pushvfstr` handles `%%`, `str_format` doesn't; each has its own type-conversion table). Factor the format-string scan into a single helper that yields tokens (`LITERAL`, `PERCENT`, `SPEC(kind, modeStr)`) and have both call sites consume those tokens. A token-driven design makes the literal-`%` case a first-class state and forces every conversion specifier (including future ones like `%q`, `%b`) to be added in exactly one place, structurally preventing "missing specifier" / "specifier consumes argument it shouldn't" bugs.
